### List Basics

A List is an ordered collection of items. Dart lists are zero-indexed and can contain any type.

```dart
void main() {
  // Creating lists
  List<int> numbers = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
  var fruits = ['apple', 'banana', 'orange'];
  var empty = <int>[];

  // Accessing elements
  print(fruits[0]); // apple
  print(fruits[1]); // banana
  print(fruits.length); // 3

  // Modifying lists
  fruits[1] = 'grape';
  fruits.add('mango');
  fruits.remove('apple');
  print(fruits);
}
```

### List Methods

| Method | Description | Example |
|--------|-------------|---------|
| `add(element)` | Adds element to end | `list.add(4)` |
| `addAll(iterable)` | Adds all elements | `list.addAll([4,5])` |
| `insert(index, element)` | Inserts at index | `list.insert(0, 'x')` |
| `remove(element)` | Removes first occurrence | `list.remove('a')` |
| `removeAt(index)` | Removes at index | `list.removeAt(0)` |
| `clear()` | Removes all elements | `list.clear()` |
| `indexOf(element)` | Finds first index | `list.indexOf('a')` |
| `contains(element)` | Checks if exists | `list.contains('a')` |
| `sort()` | Sorts the list | `list.sort()` |
| `reversed` | Returns reversed iterable | `list.reversed` |
| `sublist(start, [end])` | Returns sublist | `list.sublist(1,3)` |
| `shuffle()` | Randomizes order | `list.shuffle()` |

### List Types

```dart
void main() {
  // Fixed-length list
  var fixed = List<int>.filled(3, 0); // [0, 0, 0]
  // fixed.add(1); // ERROR: Cannot add to fixed list
  fixed[0] = 5; // OK

  // Growable list (default)
  var growable = <int>[1, 2, 3];
  growable.add(4); // OK

  // Empty typed list
  var names = <String>[];

  // List from another collection
  var set = {1, 2, 3};
  var listFromSet = set.toList();
}
```

### List Properties

```dart
void main() {
  var list = [10, 20, 30, 40, 50];

  print(list.length);   // 5
  print(list.isEmpty);  // false
  print(list.isNotEmpty); // true
  print(list.first);    // 10
  print(list.last);     // 50
  print(list.single);   // ERROR: more than one element
}
```

> **Key Point:** Dart lists grow automatically. Use `List<T>.filled()` for fixed-length lists. Use `sublist()` or `getRange()` for safe partial access.

